<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>
<!--
    Debug-only Network Security Config.

    Why this exists: starting in Android 7 (API 24), apps do NOT trust
    user-installed CA certificates by default — only system CAs. The mkcert
    root CA installed via Settings → Security → Install a certificate lands
    in the user trust store, so without an explicit opt-in, OkHttp/Ktor
    will report:
        java.security.cert.CertPathValidatorException:
        Trust anchor for certification path not found

    The fix is to declare a `<base-config>` that adds the `user` certificate
    source for debug builds. Release builds inherit Android's strict default
    (system CAs only) — so this file ONLY exists in `src/debug/`, never in
    main or release. AGP merges debug → main → release, so the manifest
    `android:networkSecurityConfig` reference resolves to this file in
    debug builds and to nothing (default policy) in release builds.

    Reference: https://developer.android.com/training/articles/security-config

    Future hardening (post-Phase 6): replace `<certificates src="user" />`
    with an explicit `<certificates src="@raw/mkcert_root" />` referencing
    a checked-in copy of mkcert's rootCA.pem under res/raw/. That avoids
    depending on the user trust store at all and is more robust to
    "I forgot to install the cert" mistakes. Skipped for now because the
    rootCA.pem is machine-specific (different per developer's mkcert install)
    and committing one developer's cert would be confusing.
-->
<network-security-config>
    <base-config cleartextTrafficPermitted="false">
        <trust-anchors>
            <!-- System CAs first (production trust store). -->
            <certificates src="system" />
            <!-- Then user-installed CAs (mkcert root, etc). -->
            <certificates src="user" />
        </trust-anchors>
    </base-config>
</network-security-config>
